To All:<br>
     Tom speaks with much merit once again.  Thanks for bringing that info up Tom.  I would like to think if I were in Lt. Cally's place or the place of one of his soldiers, that I would have done something, but what can one man do, especially if his fellow soldiers are in a frenzy.  I don't like it when people say they would have changed something if  they had been there, because each situation has to be lived through to be fully understand and to know &quot;Why&quot; or &quot;How&quot;.  I recently had a college professor, who kept saying that, and all I could say is how do you know you would have been different.  I can speculate on what happened, but having not been alive during most of the Vietnam War, my information is second hand, even if it is from reliable sources.<br>
  What I can't understand is how someone can do something horrible like shoot civilians.  Cally's Charley Company couldn't have been all bad, they were just average guys from all walks of life and different parts of America.  I may even have friends, who could be them.   When something like that happens, it must be something much more.  How can a average Grunt just shot a woman.  I AM NOT QUALIFIED TO SAY, since I was not in Vietnam (would love to visit there eventually).  All I can say is that perhaps a hatred builds up with experiences and this hatred blinds rationality.  <br>
     There are feelings that go with being a soldier in a war like Vietnam, I've seen them in my father, I've seen them in many other vets.  I wouldn't even pretend to know what it was like, but have been trying to understand since I was about 10 years old.  All I can say is that some guys jobs in Vietnam were to help the people.  My dad was with a naval construction unit (Seabees), that spent much of its tour as advisors to Vietnamese troops in III Corp area.  They also built Vietnamese housing, wells and schools.  I would have liked to serve in a unit like that, you know helping out.  <br>
     War brings a certain violence.  Did the Romans respect their prisoners 2,000 years ago-I don't think so.  I have read written accounts from the Civil War and the Napoleonic wars that talk about violence to the people and the poor treatment of prisoners.  I guess when a hatred of the enemy develops, it is hard to treat the prisoners well, and this situation is as old as warefare.<br>
     I still think that war stinks and the guys that fight it get the least out of it.  I wish for peace for the guys on both sides and all civilians caught in the middle.    I would love to hear the opinions of all you guys on this issue.  I hope I didn't run on-thanks for listening to this FNG.         
